Hey @wanderingweights (τ, τ), hoping we can discuss https://github.com/rayonlabs/G.O.D/pull/468. I believe there are some negative externalities:

**1) Punishment for iteration and improvement**
It will be extremely cumbersome to check if code improvements will not cause a regression for a subset of tasks before deploying. Miners would be heavily penalised for moving quickly, and I suspect become much more risk-averse and slow in making improvements.

**2) Unproductive burden**
Miners will be required to implement new task filtering and monitoring strategies, adding ongoing complexity and maintenance costs which otherwise could have been spent improving task performance.

**3) Validator incorrectly marks some submissions non-finetune**
The validator is prone to randomly incorrectly marking some miner submissions non-fine tune, placing onus on the miner to check every submission and ask for it to be re-evaluated if it is incorrectly marked. I don't think it's fair for miners to be penalised in these cases.

**4) Maybe most importantly, it seems easily game-able**
Instead of implementing aggressive task filtering, redundant submission strategies, intensive (and expensive!!) testing of new code across a range of tasks before deploying, a much better solution for a miner is probably to just submit a random variation of the model from HF. This sounds to me as worse for the network than had the miner not submitted anything at all.

If there are benefits that outweigh these costs and we still want to go ahead with the change, it would be great if we could discuss them. Some suggestions for mitigating the issues:

**1) A fully functioning testnet**
Testnet is missing features like a UI to check if eval was successful. If this new paradigm is introduced where we need to thoroughly test code prior to deploying, it would be great there was a testnet where functionality mirrored production we can deploy to first.

**2) There is sufficient advance notice before this is deployed**
This will allow miners time to implement, test, and deploy aggressive task filtering required to not get scores suddenly destroyed, and add alternative methods for detecting and cataloguing task/dataset incompatibilities (e.g. testnet).

**3) Do not deploy so soon after GRPO**
GRPO was only just deployed, which was a very major change many miners are still focused on implementing and optimising. 

**4) A less aggressive negative score for non-fine tunes**
Perhaps -0.1 instead of -1 to not punish experimentation as much?

**5) Improved validator eval reliability**
